).Additionally, three other scenarios were analyzed. One scenario involved the permanent enforcement of strict mobility restrictions (50%), which was projected to suppress the epidemic by the end of 2020 (Figure S-1, also depicted in Figure 4). The other two scenarios explored the effects of implementing mild restrictions from the beginning (25%) or easing restrictions before summer (to 30%); both scenarios predicted a sharp increase in the epidemic (Figure S-2 and S-3, respectively).

Figure 2 (on the following page) displays a snapshot of the model output outlining the timeline of a mitigation strategy (new hospital beds, 30-40% mobility restriction, and only severe cases tested), resulting in 660,000 recovered patients after one year. This data is based on a single simulation run, not an ensemble average.

On a later page, Figure 3 illustrates a screenshot of the model output mapping out a suppression strategy (initially 50% and later 20-25% mobility reduction with aggressive testing of mild cases and contact tracing), leading to 77,000 recovered patients after one year. Like before, these results are from a single simulation run, not an average of an ensemble.
